  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Integrated Emergency Response to Communities Affected by Drought in Eastern Africa</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The program targets the sectors of health and nutrition, water, sanitation, and hygiene, livelihood support, and shelter and protection. The program aims to respond to the immediate needs of the drought affected people in Kenya, Somalia and Ethiopia and improve their resilience to cope with future humanitarian needs. It works to ensure a consistency of service in basic curative and preventative health services to complement existing nutrition programs. In the WASH sector, it aims to provide immediate and timely support  to pastoralists and refugees  by maintaining and expanding access to lifesaving water and appropriate hygiene and sanitation practices in all target districts. The program will also improve  food security for the target  communities exposed to the impact of climate change in the target areas.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&quot;Ensure consistency of service in basic curative and preventative health services to complement existing nutrition programs; provide immediate and timely support to pastoralists and refugees by maintaining/expanding access to lifesaving water and appropriate hygiene and sanitation practices in all target districts.; Support refugee and IDP households with minimum basic shelter needs to lead dignified and secure lives; Vaccination, deworming and vitamin injections for surviving livestock; Support Irrigated Farming along River Dauwa: by providing emergency certified seed packs. To enhance food production and improved food security and livelihood, 900 farmers will be provided with certified seed packs for planting on their farms a long river Daua ;Cash for Work:   provide income at household level to the agro pastoralists along River Dauwa who will be involved in rehabilitation of irrigation canals and other farm activities through cash for work initiative.
&quot;</narrative>
  </description>
